var definitions = ['<h2>Ele passa muito tempo no seu caiaque.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the Portuguese third-person singular personal pronoun, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>passa</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "passar", which means "to spend" or "to pass". It indicates the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb meaning "a lot" or "much" in English. It’s used here to quantify the amount of time the subject spends.</div><div><strong>tempo</strong> This is a noun meaning "time" in English. It’s the object that is being quantified by "muito".</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), translating to "in the" in English. It’s used here to indicate the location or the context where the action takes place.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" in English, depending on the context. In this sentence, it’s used to indicate that the kayak belongs to the subject or to someone else, depending on the context.</div><div><strong>caiaque</strong> This is a noun meaning "kayak" which is the same as in English. It’s the object associated with the location, or the context of the action.</div>','<h2>Ela está ajudando a sua irmã menor.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary sense or to indicate location. It’s used here as an auxiliary verb to form the present continuous tense.</div><div><strong>ajudando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "ajudar", which means "to help". It’s used here after the verb "estar" to form the present continuous tense, meaning "helping".</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article "the" in Portuguese. However, it’s also used before "sua irmã menor" as part of the verb "ajudar a", an expression that translates to "to help".</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective meaning "her" or "your" in English, in a formal context. It shows that the sister belongs or is related to the subject "Ela".</div><div><strong>irmã</strong> This is a noun that means "sister" in English. It’s the object of the action. </div><div><strong>menor</strong> This is an adjective meaning "younger" or "smallest". When paired with "irmã", it means "younger sister". It ensures the meaning that the sister being helped is younger than the subject.</div>','<h2>Ele vai ao parque com os seus pais.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the Portuguese pronoun for "he". It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>vai</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the verb "ir" in Present Simple, which means "to go".</div><div><strong>ao</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) and the definite article "o" (the), which in English translates to "to the".</div><div><strong>parque</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "park".</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition for "with".</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine, plural nouns, meaning "the".</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese and here it means "his" or "her". In this context, it’s "his" since "Ele" refers to a male subject.</div><div><strong>pais</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "parents".</div>','<h2>Ela dormiu sobre as suas anotações.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dormiu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "dormir", which means "to sleep". It indicates that the action was completed in the past.</div><div><strong>sobre</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can translate to "over" or "on" in English, indicating the position of one thing in relation to another.</div><div><strong>as</strong> This is the feminine plural definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to refer to specific notes.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese and can translate as "her" in English, indicating that the notes belong to the subject, "she".</div><div><strong>anotações</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "anotação", which means "notes". It denotes items on which someone writes down information, observations, etc.</div>','<h2>A sua casa.</h2><div><strong>A</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article "the". It agrees in gender and number with the noun it precedes, and in this case, it’s feminine and singular because it is referring to "casa" which is feminine.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English when referring to one person in a formal context or "his/her" in an informal context. The possessiveness is associated with "casa". It also agrees with the gender and number of the noun it modifies, which is again feminine singular in this case.</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "house" or "home". It is the subject of the sentence, and as mentioned earlier, it is feminine singular.</div>','<h2>O seu irmão</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here in the masculine singular form to match the gender and number of the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English, in the context of formal address, or "his", "her", "its", or "their" depending on the context. In this sentence, it’s ambiguous without additional context. It matches the masculine singular form of the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>irmão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "brother". It is in the masculine singular form.</div>','<h2>As suas caixas de mudança.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the feminine plural definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes feminine plural nouns.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which can be translated as "your" in English when formal or "his/her/their" in an informal context, indicating ownership or association with the subject, in this case referring to "boxes". It agrees in gender and number with the nouns it modifies, which here is feminine and plural.</div><div><strong>caixas</strong> This is the plural form of the Portuguese noun "caixa", which means "boxes" in English. It’s a feminine noun in plural form as it is talking about more than one box.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese commonly translated to "of" in English. It is used for indicating relationships, such as possession or connection between nouns.</div><div><strong>mudança</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "move" or "moving" when referring to the act of changing residence or location. It is a singular feminine noun and, in this context, is associated with the boxes used for packing and transporting items during a move.</div>','<h2>Você está andando de bicicleta com os seus amigos.</h2><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English, specifically in its continuous or progressive form. It is used here to describe an ongoing action the subject is currently performing.</div><div><strong>andando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "andar", which means "to walk" or, in this context, "to ride" when referring to a bike. In English, it would be the equivalent of "-ing" form of a verb, used to indicate an action in progress (riding).</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "from", "of", or "about". In this context, it is part of the phrase "andando de bicicleta", which translates to "riding a bike", using "de" to link the action of riding with the bicycle.</div><div><strong>bicicleta</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese which means "bicycle" in English.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "with" in English. It is used to indicate accompaniment or participation in an action.</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the masculine plural definite article in Portuguese, translating to "the" in English. It is used here to specify the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which can be translated as "your" in English. It’s in the masculine plural form to agree with the masculine plural noun that follows and to indicate possession by the subject "você".</div><div><strong>amigos</strong> This is the masculine plural form of the noun "amigo", which means "friends" in English. The word "seus" before it indicates that these are the friends of the subject "você".</div>','<h2>O seu cachorro</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article for masculine singular nouns in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese. It means "your" in English and is used here to indicate possession, showing that the dog belongs to the person being spoken to. Please note that "seu" could also mean "his" or "her", depending on the context, as Portuguese does not distinguish possessive adjectives by gender of the possessor.</div><div><strong>cachorro</strong> This is a common noun in Portuguese, meaning "dog" in English. It refers to a domestic pet canine.</div>','<h2>Os seus pais</h2><div><strong>Os</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article in the masculine plural form, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here to define a specific group being referred to.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that can be translated as "your" in English. It is in the masculine plural form to match the noun it modifies and implies ownership or relation. Depending on the context, it can also be interpreted as "his", "her", or "their", showing possession by a third party.</div><div><strong>pais</strong> This is a Portuguese noun in the plural form, meaning "parents". It refers to a person’s father and mother collectively.</div>','<h2>Eles estão brincando com a sua corda.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary or location state in Portuguese. It is used here to describe a current ongoing action.</div><div><strong>brincando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "brincar", which means "to play". It indicates an ongoing action and is analogous to the English -ing form.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "with". It’s used here to introduce the object of the action.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese that means "your" (singular or plural formal) or "his/her/its/their" (singular or plural), depending on the context. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which is "corda" in this case.</div><div><strong>corda</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in Portuguese, which means "rope". It’s the object being played with in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Eles estão escutando as suas músicas favoritas.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present tense of the verb "estar", which means "to be". It indicates an ongoing action or state.</div><div><strong>escutando</strong> This is the present participle or gerund form of the verb "escutar", which means "to listen". In combination with "estão", it forms the present continuous tense, indicating an action that is currently happening.</div><div><strong>as</strong> This is the definite article for feminine plural nouns in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It refers to the "músicas" that follows.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in feminine plural form, which can be translated to "their" or "your" in English, depending on the context. It indicates possession of the "músicas" by the person or persons referred to by the subject.</div><div><strong>músicas</strong> This is the plural form of the feminine noun "música", which means "music" or "songs" in English. Here, it’s the direct object of the verb "escutar".</div><div><strong>favoritas</strong> This is the feminine plural form of the adjective "favorito", meaning "favorite" in English. It modifies the noun "músicas", specifying a particular kind of songs.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Ele deu seus primeiros passos hoje.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the Portuguese third-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deu</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "dar", which means "to give". However, in this context, it indicates a completion of action, similar to "took" as in "he took his first steps".</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is the masculine plural possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates that the following noun "primeiros passos" belongs to the subject "Ele".</div><div><strong>primeiros</strong> This is the masculine plural form of the ordinal adjective "primeiro", meaning "first" in English. It modifies the noun "passos", indicating that these are the initial instances of the action.</div><div><strong>passos</strong> This is the plural form of the Portuguese noun "passo", which translates to "steps" in English. Combined with the previous elements, it indicates that the subject "Ele" completed the action of taking "steps" for the first time.</div><div><strong>hoje</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "today". It denotes the time when the action of taking the first steps occurred.</div>','<h2>O encanador pôde terminar seu trabalho.</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>encanador</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese meaning "plumber". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pôde</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to". Here, it indicates that the plumber was able to do something in the past.</div><div><strong>terminar</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese meaning "to finish" or "to complete". It’s the action the plumber was able to do.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" (formal singular) depending on the context. It indicates possession or relationship to the subject.</div><div><strong>trabalho</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese meaning "work" or "job". It is the object that was finished by the plumber.</div>','<h2>Ele tem que pagar com seu cartão de crédito.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ter" in the present tense, which means "to have" in English. In this sentence, it is part of the expression "tem que", which means "has to" or "must".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This word translates to "that" in English, but when used with "tem", as in "tem que", it means "to have to" or "must". It is used to express necessity or obligation.</div><div><strong>pagar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to pay" in Portuguese. It indicates the action that must be performed.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese meaning "with" in English. It indicates the means by which the payment will be made.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that translates to "his" or "your" in English, depending on the context. In this sentence, it’s likely to mean "his", referring to the subject "Ele", unless the context suggests a formal "you".</div><div><strong>cartão</strong> This is a masculine noun in Portuguese that means "card" in English. It specifies the type of card used for the payment.</div><div><strong>de crédito</strong> This phrase means "credit" in English, completing the noun phrase "credit card". "De" is a preposition meaning "of", and "crédito" is the noun meaning "credit".</div>','<h2>Cada estudante tem seu próprio computador.</h2><div><strong>Cada</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "each" or "every". It is used to indicate that the statement applies to every individual member of the following group.</div><div><strong>estudante</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "student". It refers to an individual who is studying, typically at an academic institution.</div><div><strong>tem</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. It indicates possession or ownership.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This Portuguese possessive adjective translates to "his", "her", "its", or "their" in English, depending on the context. In this case, it means "their own" as it refers to something that each student possesses individually.</div><div><strong>próprio</strong> This is a Portuguese adjective that means "own", emphasizing that the object of possession is exclusive to the subject.</div><div><strong>computador</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "computer". It refers to the electronic device that is capable of receiving, processing, and presenting data.</div>','<h2>Ele precisa telefonar para o seu colega de trabalho.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "He" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>precisa</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "precisar", which means "to need". In this sentence, it indicates a requirement or necessity.</div><div><strong>telefonar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "telefonar", which means "to call" or "to phone" in English. It indicates the action that the subject needs to do.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "to" in English. It is used here to indicate direction or destination of the action.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This word is the definite article "the" in English, in its masculine singular form in Portuguese. It precedes the noun "colega".</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" (formal) in English, depending on the context. In this sentence, it’s used to denote ownership or association, as in "his colleague".</div><div><strong>colega</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "colleague" in English. It refers to a person with whom one works, particularly in a profession or business.</div><div><strong>de trabalho</strong> This is a prepositional phrase composed of the preposition "de" (meaning "of") and the noun "trabalho" (meaning "work"). Together, they qualify the type of colleague, effectively meaning "work colleague" or "co-worker".</div>','<h2>Ele está lavando seu carro, porque está sujo.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It’s used here to denote a continuous action or state.</div><div><strong>lavando</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "lavar", meaning "washing" in English. It indicates an action currently in progress.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "his" or "her" in English. It denotes ownership of the car. The gender of the owner is not specified by this word in Portuguese.</div><div><strong>carro</strong> This is a noun meaning "car" in English.</div><div><strong>porque</strong> This is a conjunction that means "because" in English. It introduces a cause or reason.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is repeated from earlier and once again is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar". Here it precedes an adjective describing the state of the car.</div><div><strong>sujo</strong> This is an adjective meaning "dirty" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it describes, which is "carro" (singular masculine).</div>','<h2>Tem ketchup e mostarda em seu cachorro-quente.</h2><div><strong>Tem</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. In this context, it suggests the presence of something, akin to "there is/are" or "has" in English.</div><div><strong>ketchup</strong> This is a loanword from English, remaining the same in Portuguese. It refers to a sweet and tangy sauce usually made from tomatoes, vinegar, and a variety of seasonings and spices—and is a popular condiment.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It is a conjunction used to connect words or phrases of the same type.</div><div><strong>mostarda</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "mustard", which is a condiment typically made from mustard seeds and vinegar, often used on sandwiches and hot dogs.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition that can have various meanings depending on the context, but here it translates to "in" or "on" in English, indicating the location of the ketchup and mustard.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that translates to "your" in English, denoting ownership or belonging.</div><div><strong>cachorro-quente</strong> This is the Portuguese term for "hot dog", which is a cooked sausage usually served in a partly sliced bun and often topped with various condiments.</div>','<h2>Ele amarrava seus sapatos antes da partida de tênis.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>amarrava</strong> This is the third-person singular imperfect tense form of the verb "amarrar", which means "to tie". It indicates an action that was ongoing or habitual in the past. </div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "his" in English. It indicates that the shoes belong to him.</div><div><strong>sapatos</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "shoes". It is a masculine plural noun.</div><div><strong>antes</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "before". It’s a preposition used to indicate time in relation to another event.</div><div><strong>da</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "de" (of / from) and the article "a" (the), forming "da". In this context, it translates to "of the" or "before the", relating to the tennis match.</div><div><strong>partida</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "match" or "game". It is a feminine singular noun.</div><div><strong>de</strong> Here, this preposition means "of" indicating the type of match or game.</div><div><strong>tênis</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "tennis". It is a masculine singular noun and, in this sentence, is used to specify the type of match being referred to.</div>','<h2>Ela adora brincar com seu cachorro.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>adora</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "adorar", which means "to love" or "to adore". It suggests a great affection or enjoyment for something.</div><div><strong>brincar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "brincar", which means "to play". In this sentence, it’s used to describe the action she enjoys doing.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that means "with". It is used to indicate association or accompaniment.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective that can mean "his", "her", or "its" in English. The exact meaning depends on context, but here it likely means "her" since the subject is "Ela" (she).</div><div><strong>cachorro</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "dog". It’s the object of the action described in the sentence (the entity with which "Ela" is playing).</div>','<h2>Ela lavará o interior de seu forno.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>lavará</strong> This is the future tense form of the verb "lavar", which means "to wash". It indicates an action that will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>o interior</strong> This is a noun phrase where "o" is the definite article "the" and "interior" means "inside" or "interior". Combined, this phrase refers to the inside part of something, in this case, the oven.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition that can have several meanings depending on the context. Here it is used to indicate possession, equivalent to "of" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "your" (formal) in English, depending on the context. In this sentence, it suggests the oven belongs to the person being spoken about or spoken to in a formal context.</div><div><strong>forno</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "oven". It’s a common kitchen appliance used for baking or cooking.</div>','<h2>Ela fechará a porta de seu quarto de hotel.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fechará</strong> This is the third-person singular future tense form of the verb "fechar", which means "to close". It indicates a future action that she will perform.</div><div><strong>a porta</strong> This phrase translates to "the door" in English. "A" is the definite article for a feminine noun, and "porta" is the noun referring to the object that will be closed.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can mean "of" or "from". It’s used here to indicate possession.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This possessive pronoun means "your" in English and denotes ownership. In this context, it can also be understood as "her" since it refers back to the subject "Ela" due to the lack of context indicating another person.</div><div><strong>quarto</strong> This word translates to "room" in English. It is a masculine noun that receives the possessive pronoun "seu".</div><div><strong>de hotel</strong> This phrase means "of hotel" or "hotel’s" in English. It describes the type of room being referred to. "De" is the preposition and "hotel" is the noun.</div>','<h2>Ela pegava a câmera de seu pai.</h2><div><strong>Ela</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pegava</strong> This is the third-person singular imperfect tense form of the verb "pegar", which means "to take" or "to grab". The imperfect tense indicates a continuous or habitual past action.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s feminine and singular to agree with "câmera".</div><div><strong>câmera</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "camera". It’s feminine and singular.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can translate to "of" or "from" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese. It can mean "his", "her", "its", or "their" depending on context. In this sentence, it means "her" as it refers to "pai" (father), which is masculine and singular.</div><div><strong>pai</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "father". It is masculine and singular.</div>','<h2>Ele é muito bom com sua bicicleta.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It describes the state of being or identity of the subject.</div><div><strong>muito</strong> This is an adverb in Portuguese meaning "very" or "much" in English. Its function is to modify the adjective that follows, intensifying its meaning.</div><div><strong>bom</strong> This Portuguese adjective means "good" in English. It is used here to qualify how the subject is with his bicycle, matching the masculine and singular form to agree with the subject.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that translates to "with" in English. It is used to indicate the association between the subject and his bicycle.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "his" or "her" in English (contextually, here it means "his"). It agrees in gender and number with the noun it refers to, which is "bicicleta".</div><div><strong>bicicleta</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in Portuguese, which translates to "bicycle" in English. It’s the object of the preposition "com", completing the phrase.</div>','<h2>Ele tira fotos para se lembrar de sua viagem.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>tira</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "tirar", which can mean "to take" or "to pull" in English. In this context, it means "to take", referring to taking photos.</div><div><strong>fotos</strong> This is the plural form of "foto", which is a noun in Portuguese that translates to "photos" in English. It’s the direct object of the verb "tira", indicating what he is taking.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, which in this context means "to" or "in order to". It introduces the purpose of taking photos.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. In this sentence, it is used in conjunction with the verb "lembrar", forming a reflexive verb "lembrar-se" that means "to remember oneself" or simply "to remember".</div><div><strong>lembrar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember" in English. Connected with the reflexive pronoun "se", it indicates the action of recalling or retaining memory.</div><div><strong>de sua</strong> "de sua" is a combination of the preposition "de", which can mean "of" or "from" in this case, and the possessive pronoun "sua", which means "his" or "her" depending on the context (in this case, "his").</div><div><strong>viagem</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "trip" or "journey" in English. Combined with "de sua", it specifies what he is remembering – "his trip".</div>','<h2>Então, você o ajudou com sua lição de casa?</h2><div><strong>Então</strong> This Portuguese word translates to "so" or "then" in English. It is often used as a conversational connector or to start a question or statement.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is a direct object masculine pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "him" or "it" in English. It refers back to a previously mentioned or assumed masculine noun that is receiving the action.</div><div><strong>ajudou</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "ajudar", which means "to help". Here, it indicates that the helping action has been completed in the past.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "with" in English. It introduces the object of the action, showing association.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, which translates to "your" in English. It agrees with the noun "lição de casa", which is feminine, to show possession.</div><div><strong>lição de casa</strong> This Portuguese phrase means "homework". "Lição" means "lesson" and "de casa" indicates that it is work to be done at home. Combined, they refer to the assignments given by a teacher to be completed outside of class.</div>','<h2>Ele pulou sobre um galho com sua prancha de snowboard.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>pulou</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "pular", which means "to jump". It indicates an action performed by the subject in the past.</div><div><strong>sobre</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "over" or "above". It indicates the relationship between the action of jumping and the object (galho).</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a Portuguese indefinite article in the masculine singular form, meaning "a" in English. It is used here before the noun "galho".</div><div><strong>galho</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "branch". In this sentence, it’s the object over which the subject jumped.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "with", indicating the instrument or means by which the action was performed.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "his" in English. It implies ownership of the snowboard by the subject.</div><div><strong>prancha</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "board". It is commonly used to refer to different kinds of boards used in sports, such as "prancha de surf" for surfboard.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition typically translated as "of" in English. In this context, it’s used to link "prancha" with "snowboard", to specify the type of board.</div><div><strong>snowboard</strong> This is a loanword in Portuguese from English, referring to the winter sport equipment used for snowboarding. It remains unchanged in Portuguese spelling.</div>','<h2>Ele ajudou suas irmãs mais novas a subir a colina.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "He" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ajudou</strong> This is the past tense form of the verb "ajudar", which means "to help". In this sentence, it indicates that the action has been completed in the past.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is the possessive adjective meaning "his, her, its, their", used here to refer to "his" own in feminine plural form, matching the gender and number of "irmãs" (sisters).</div><div><strong>irmãs</strong> This is a noun in the plural form meaning "sisters". The word is feminine plural to match the possessed noun that it refers to.</div><div><strong>mais novas</strong> This phrase is composed of "mais" (more) and "novas" (young) together meaning "younger". It’s a comparative phrase describing the sisters as younger than either him or other sisters.</div><div><strong>a subir</strong> This is the infinitive verb "subir", prefixed by the preposition "a". It indicates the action of climbing or going up.</div><div><strong>a colina</strong> This phrase means "the hill". "Colina" is a feminine singular noun, and "a" is the feminine singular article, translating to "the".</div>','<h2>Ele não consegue consertar o carro sem suas ferramentas.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>não</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "not". It negates a statement or responds negatively to a sentence.</div><div><strong>consegue</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "conseguir", which means "to manage" or "to be able to". It indicates the subject’s capability.</div><div><strong>consertar</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese meaning "to repair" or "to fix". It is the action that the subject cannot perform without the tools.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>carro</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "car". It is a masculine singular noun and the object being repaired.</div><div><strong>sem</strong> This is the Portuguese preposition meaning "without". It explains the condition under which the subject cannot repair the car.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, meaning "his" or "her" in English. In this sentence, it refers to "his" because the subject is male. It’s plural because it modifies the plural noun "ferramentas".</div><div><strong>ferramentas</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "tools". It is plural because it refers to multiple items used for repair.</div>','<h2>Ele dá um presente de Natal à sua irmã mais nova.</h2><div><strong>Ele</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "He" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dá</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "dar", which means "to give". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is the indefinite article in Portuguese, singular masculine form, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes a masculine singular noun.</div><div><strong>presente de Natal</strong> This phrase means "Christmas gift" in Portuguese. "Presente" is a noun meaning "gift" and "de Natal" is a possessive phrase that denotes the gift is related to Christmas.</div><div><strong>à</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "a" (to) and the definite article "a" (the) in Portuguese. It denotes the direction or recipient of the action.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "his" or "her" in English. It’s used here to express that the sister belongs to the subject, in the sense that she is his sister.</div><div><strong>irmã</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "sister". It’s a noun representing the female sibling.</div><div><strong>mais nova</strong> This phrase means "younger" in Portuguese, coming from "mais" (more) and "nova" (new, but used in this context as "young"). It describes that the sister is younger than the subject.</div>','<h2>Qual é o seu nome?</h2><div><strong>Qual</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "which" or "what". It is used here to initiate a question about information.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be" in English. It’s used to link the subject with attributes or complement.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is a definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is masculine and singular to match "nome" (name).</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It denotes ownership or association with the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>nome?</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "name". It is a common noun used in questions about personal identification. The question mark indicates that it is part of an interrogative sentence.</div>','<h2>Eu posso ver o seu passaporte?</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>posso</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates ability or permission.</div><div><strong>ver</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese that means "to see". It is used here in combination with "posso" (can) to form the phrase "can see".</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes "passaporte" to specify the passport being referred to.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "your". It shows possession or belonging to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>passaporte?</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese which means "passport". It’s the object of the verb "ver" (see), indicating what the speaker wants to see.</div>','<h2>Eu quis dizer o seu tamanho de sapato.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>quis</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense of the verb "querer", which means "to want". In this case, it conveys a past action or intention, often translated as "I wanted" or "I meant".</div><div><strong>dizer</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to say" or "to tell" in Portuguese. Following "quis", it helps to formulate the past intention "I meant to say".</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which means "your" in English. It shows ownership or relation to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>tamanho</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "size". It references the dimension or magnitude of an object or, in this case, a clothing or shoe size.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is the preposition "of" in Portuguese. It is used here to link "tamanho" (size) and "sapato" (shoe) semantically.</div><div><strong>sapato</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "shoe". It is a masculine singular noun.</div>','<h2>Obrigado! Aqui está o seu troco.</h2><div><strong>Obrigado!</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "thank you". It’s used by males. If a female were speaking, she would say "Obrigada!"</div><div><strong>Aqui</strong> This Portuguese word means "here". It indicates the place where the speaker is or a place relative to the conversation.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in English. It’s used for temporary states or locations.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "your". It is used here to show ownership or association with the listener.</div><div><strong>troco</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "change", as in money given back after a purchase.</div>','<h2>Posso entrar no seu escritório?</h2><div><strong>Posso</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates the speaker’s ability or permission to do something.</div><div><strong>entrar</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese which translates to "to enter" in English. It is the main action that the speaker is asking permission to do.</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the definite article "o" (the), together meaning "in the" or "on the". In Portuguese, contractions are common and required before definite articles.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, which translates to "your" in English. It indicates ownership or association with the person being spoken to (second-person).</div><div><strong>escritório</strong> This is a Portuguese noun which means "office". It is the place the speaker is asking permission to enter.</div><div><strong>?</strong> This symbol denotes that the sentence is a question, indicating that the speaker is looking for a response or confirmation.</div>','<h2>Eu posso ver o seu cartão de embarque?</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>posso</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "to be able to" or "can". It indicates ability or possibility in this context.</div><div><strong>ver</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese meaning "to see". In this sentence, it indicates the action that the subject wants to perform.</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for masculine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese meaning "your". It indicates that the boarding pass belongs to the person being spoken to. Note that it agrees in gender and number with the noun it refers to.</div><div><strong>cartão</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese meaning "card".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese that can be translated as "of" or "from" in English. In this context, it is used to link "cartão" with "embarque" to form the phrase "boarding pass".</div><div><strong>embarque</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese meaning "boarding". Combined with "cartão" it forms the term for "boarding pass".</div>','<h2>O que você faz no seu tempo livre?</h2><div><strong>O</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "the" when referring to a masculine noun or the beginning of a question. It’s used here as part of an interrogative phrase.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is the Portuguese relative and interrogative pronoun meaning "what" or "that". It is used here to introduce a question.</div><div><strong>você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s commonly used in both informal and formal settings.</div><div><strong>faz</strong> This is the third-person singular present indicative form of the verb "fazer", which means "to do" or "to make". In this sentence, it is conjugated to match "você".</div><div><strong>no</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) and the masculine singular definite article "o" (the) in Portuguese. It translates to "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective meaning "your" in English. It indicates possession or association with the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>tempo</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "time".</div><div><strong>livre?</strong> This is an adjective meaning "free". In this context, it refers to time that is free from obligations, roughly translating to "free time" or "spare time" in English.</div>','<h2>Pode me passar o seu número de telefone?</h2><div><strong>Pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present of the verb "poder", which means "can" or "be able to". Here, it’s used as a formal or polite request.</div><div><strong>me</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "me" in English. It is used as an indirect object in this sentence.</div><div><strong>passar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "passar", which means "to pass" or "to give". In this context, it means "to give" or "to provide".</div><div><strong>o</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, used here before "seu número de telefone" (your telephone number) to specify it.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that means "your" in English. It denotes ownership of the telephone number.</div><div><strong>número</strong> This is a noun which means "number" in English.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition that means "of" in English.</div><div><strong>telefone</strong> This is a noun which means "telephone" in English.</div><div><strong>?</strong> The question mark indicates that the sentence is a question, seeking information or requesting an action.</div>','<h2>Certo. O senhor pode inserir o seu cartão.</h2><div><strong>Certo</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "Right" or "Okay", often used to confirm understanding or agreement.</div><div><strong>O senhor</strong> This is a formal way to address a man in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or "mister" in English, reflecting respect or formality.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "poder" in present indicative, meaning "can" or "may" in English. It indicates capability or permission.</div><div><strong>inserir</strong> This is an infinitive verb that means "to insert". It is part of an instruction or directive in this sentence.</div><div><strong>o seu</strong> This phrase means "your" in English, with "o" being the masculine singular definite article "the", and "seu" indicating possession, with a masculine singular noun.</div><div><strong>cartão</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "card", which can refer to various types of cards, such as credit cards or debit cards.</div>','<h2>Aqui está a sua gorjeta...</h2><div><strong>Aqui</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "here". It indicates the location or the place where the speaker is currently at.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It serves to indicate the place or state of being.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is feminine singular and matches the gender and number of the noun (gorjeta) it modifies.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "your". In this context, it’s in the feminine singular form, agreeing with the noun (gorjeta) and referring to the listener’s tip.</div><div><strong>gorjeta</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "tip", referring to a small amount of money given to someone for their service. Here it’s in the singular form, referred to within the context of a singular event.</div>','<h2>Como é a sua casa?</h2><div><strong>Como</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "how". It is used to start questions regarding the manner, condition, or quality of something.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "ser", which means "to be". It links the subject to a complement that describes its characteristics or identity.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for feminine singular nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It denotes ownership or association with the person being spoken to and agrees in gender with the noun it modifies, which in this case is "casa" (a feminine noun).</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "house" or "home". It is a feminine noun and the main subject of inquiry in the sentence.</div><div>? This punctuation marks the sentence as a question, indicating that the speaker is asking for information about the listener’s house.</div>','<h2>Certo. Aqui está a sua água.</h2><div><strong>Certo</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "right" or "sure", often used to express agreement or acknowledgement.</div><div><strong>Aqui</strong> This is the Portuguese adverb meaning "here". It indicates the location.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "estar" in Portuguese, which means "to be" in English. It is used here to denote the presence or location of something.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for feminine nouns, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes a feminine noun or adjective. </div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It indicates that the water belongs to the person being spoken to. It is in the feminine form to agree with the noun "água".</div><div><strong>água</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "water". It is a feminine noun.</div>','<h2>Como foi a sua viagem ao Brasil?</h2><div><strong>Como</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "how". It is used to start a question regarding the manner, condition, or quality of something.</div><div><strong>foi</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "ser" or "ir" in Portuguese, meaning "was" or "went" respectively. Here, it likely refers to "was", as part of the phrase that translates to "how was".</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the Portuguese definite article for the feminine singular, which means "the" in English. It precedes feminine singular nouns.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "your" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the thing being possessed, in this case, the feminine singular word "viagem" (trip).</div><div><strong>viagem</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "trip" or "journey" in English. It is feminine and singular in this context.</div><div><strong>ao</strong> This is a contraction of the Portuguese preposition "a" (to) and the masculine definite article "o" (the), which together mean "to the" in English when referring to masculine nouns. Since the word "Brasil" is a masculine noun in Portuguese, the preposition "a" contracts with "o" to become "ao".</div><div><strong>Brasil?</strong> This is the Portuguese name for Brazil, a country in South America. It is a proper noun and is masculine in Portuguese.</div>','<h2>Muito bem... Aqui está a sua mesa.</h2><div><strong>Muito bem</strong> This is a Portuguese phrase meaning "very well" or "okay". It expresses approval or acknowledgment, often used when an agreement is reached or to indicate that everything is in order.</div><div><strong>Aqui</strong> This word translates to "here" in English. It denotes the location relative to the speaker.</div><div><strong>está</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in Portuguese. It’s used here to denote the position or state of something.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s feminine singular to agree with the noun "mesa".</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese that means "your". It’s used here in the feminine singular form to agree with the noun "mesa" and indicates ownership or association with the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>mesa</strong> This is a noun meaning "table" in Portuguese. In this context, it refers to the dining table that has been prepared or arranged for the customer.</div>','<h2>Vou preparar a sua medicação.</h2><div><strong>Vou</strong> Esta é a primeira pessoa do singular do presente do indicativo do verbo "ir" em português. Ele indica ação futura, equivalente em inglês ao uso de will/shall (ex: "I will" prepare). Aqui, é usado para expressar uma ação que o falante pretende realizar no futuro.</div><div><strong>preparar</strong> Este é o verbo principal da frase, no infinitivo, que significa "to prepare" em inglês. Refere-se à ação de preparar algo, nesse caso, a medicação de alguém.</div><div><strong>a sua</strong> Esta é uma combinação do artigo definido feminino singular "a" com o pronome possessivo "sua". Juntos, esses elementos são usados para indicar posse ou associação, neste contexto, significando "your" em inglês, referindo-se à medicação da pessoa a quem o falante se dirige.</div><div><strong>medicação</strong> Este é um substantivo feminino singular que significa "medication" em inglês. Refere-se a um conjunto de medicamentos que foram prescritos para uma pessoa.</div>','<h2>Esta é a sua opinião ou um fato?</h2><div><strong>Esta</strong> This is the feminine singular demonstrative pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "this" in English. It refers to something close to the speaker.</div><div><strong>é</strong> This is the third-person singular of the verb "ser" in Portuguese, which means "to be". It’s used to link the subject with the predicate.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s in the feminine singular form to agree with the noun it precedes.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It’s in the feminine singular form to agree with the noun it modifies.</div><div><strong>opinião</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "opinion". It’s in the singular form and denotes a personal view, belief, or judgment.</div><div><strong>ou</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese meaning "or". It’s used to link alternatives or choices.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is an indefinite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It’s in the masculine singular form because the word it precedes is masculine.</div><div><strong>fato</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "fact". It’s in the singular form and refers to something that is known or proved to be true.</div><div><strong>?</strong> This symbol indicates that the sentence is a question. It’s used at the end of a sentence in both Portuguese and English.</div>','<h2>Tudo bem. O senhor pode inserir a sua senha.</h2><div><strong>Tudo</strong> This is a Portuguese word meaning "everything" or "all". It is often used in the expression "Tudo bem", which means "All good" or "Everything’s fine".</div><div><strong>bem</strong> This is a Portuguese adverb meaning "well". In the context of the phrase "Tudo bem", it is part of the common informal greeting, which is equivalent to asking "How are you?" or saying "I’m well" in English.</div><div><strong>O</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, meaning "the". It is used here to specify the noun that follows and is masculine singular to agree with "senhor".</div><div><strong>senhor</strong> This is a respectful form of address in Portuguese, equivalent to "sir" or "mister" in English. It is used here as a formal way to address a man.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "can" or "to be able to". It indicates ability or permission.</div><div><strong>inserir</strong> This is an infinitive verb meaning "to insert" or "to enter" in Portuguese. It is used here to indicate the action that the gentleman can perform.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, meaning "the". It is used here to specify the noun that follows and is feminine singular to agree with "senha".</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "your" (formal). It indicates that the password belongs to the person being addressed.</div><div><strong>senha</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "password". It refers to a series of characters used for authentication or to gain access to something, such as a personal account.</div>','<h2>Entendi. Você pode levantar a sua manga?</h2><div><strong>Entendi</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "entender", which means "to understand" in English. It indicates that the speaker has grasped or comprehended something.</div><div><strong>Você</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s often used in a formal or polite context.</div><div><strong>pode</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "poder", which means "can" or "to be able to" in English. It suggests ability or permission.</div><div><strong>levantar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "levantar", which means "to lift" or "to raise" in English. Here, it is used after another verb to indicate an action to be taken.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is a definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which is "manga" in this case.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "your" in English. It shows ownership or relation of the following noun, "manga", to the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>manga</strong> This is a common noun in Portuguese, meaning "sleeve" in English. It’s the object of the action described by the verb "levantar".</div>','<h2>Eles deveriam escutar seu professor.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>deveriam</strong> This is the third-person plural form of the past imperfect subjunctive of the verb "dever", which means "should" or "ought to". It indicates an unfulfilled condition or expectation in the past.</div><div><strong>escutar</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese meaning "to listen" or "to hear". It connects with "deveriam" to express what the subject should have done.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese that can mean "his", "her", "its", or "their", depending on the context. Since there’s no indication of gender or number, it’s ambiguous without further information. Here, it matches "professor" and is assumed to mean "their" referring back to "Eles".</div><div><strong>professor</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "teacher". It serves as the object of the sentence, the person that "they" should listen to.</div>','<h2>As crianças têm que conhecer seu alfabeto.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, equivalent to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>crianças</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "children". It is in the plural form and is a feminine noun agreeing with the article "as".</div><div><strong>têm</strong> This is the third-person plural of the present indicative tense of the verb "ter" in Portuguese, which means "have". It indicates possession or necessity when followed by "que".</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a conjunction in Portuguese often translated as "that" in English. When used with "têm", it indicates an obligation or a necessity, i.e., "have to".</div><div><strong>conhecer</strong> This is an infinitive verb in Portuguese which means "to know" or "to be familiar with". In this context, it refers to knowing or learning something, like the alphabet.</div><div><strong>seu</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese meaning "his/her/its/their". In this context, it is used in the singular form and can be understood to mean "their".</div><div><strong>alfabeto</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in Portuguese that means "alphabet". It refers to the set of letters used in writing an alphabetized language, in this case implying the Portuguese alphabet the children must learn.</div>','<h2>Eles estão dormindo na cama de seus pais.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "They" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>estão</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "estar", which means "to be" in a temporary or location sense. In this context, it indicates a current ongoing action.</div><div><strong>dormindo</strong> This is the gerund form of the verb "dormir", which means "to sleep". Combined with "estão", it forms the present continuous tense, expressing the action of sleeping that is happening now.</div><div><strong>na</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "em" (in) with the definite article "a" (the), which is the feminine singular form. It translates to "in the" in English.</div><div><strong>cama</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "bed". It’s the object of the preposition "na", indicating location.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a Portuguese preposition meaning "of" or "from", indicating possession in this case.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that means "their" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which in this case is the plural "pais" (parents).</div><div><strong>pais</strong> This is a Portuguese noun that means "parents". It’s the object of the preposition "de", telling us whose bed they are sleeping in.</div>','<h2>Eu quero que eles resolvam seus problemas.</h2><div><strong>Eu</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>quero</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "querer", which means "to want". In this sentence, it indicates a desire or wish by the subject.</div><div><strong>que</strong> In this context, "que" is a conjunction used to introduce a dependent clause. It translates to "that" in English.</div><div><strong>eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the dependent clause.</div><div><strong>resolvam</strong> This is the third-person plural present subjunctive tense form of the verb "resolver", which means "to solve" or "to resolve". The subjunctive mood is used here to express a wish or a desire about something uncertain or hypothetical.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "their" in English. It agrees in gender and number with the noun it modifies, which is "problemas".</div><div><strong>problemas</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese meaning "problems". It’s the direct object of the verb "resolvam", indicating what should be solved.</div>','<h2>Elas esperavam seus pais para abrir os presentes de Natal.</h2><div><strong>Elas</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a group of female individuals. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>esperavam</strong> This is the third-person plural imperfect indicative form of the verb "esperar", which means "to wait" or "to expect" in English. It indicates a past ongoing action.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "their" in English. It indicates that the parents belong to or are associated with "elas" (they).</div><div><strong>pais</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "parents". It’s the direct object in the sentence, the individuals "they" were waiting for.</div><div><strong>para</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, which translates to "to" or "in order to" in English. It introduces the purpose or goal of the waiting.</div><div><strong>abrir</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "abrir", which means "to open" in English. It suggests the action they want to perform.</div><div><strong>os</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, "the" in English. It precedes and defines the noun "presentes" (gifts).</div><div><strong>presentes</strong> This is a noun in Portuguese that means "presents" or "gifts" in English. It’s the object of the action "abrir" (to open).</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, which can be translated as "of" or "from" in English. It is used here to indicate possession or association.</div><div><strong>Natal</strong> This is a noun meaning "Christmas" in English. It specifies the type of presents they were waiting to open.</div>','<h2>Elas fizeram a lição de casa e depois brincaram com seus brinquedos.</h2><div><strong>Elas</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a group of females. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fizeram</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "fazer", which means "to do" or "to make". In this sentence, it indicates a completed action of doing, specifically, doing their homework.</div><div><strong>a lição de casa</strong> This phrase translates to "the homework". "Liçao" is the word for "lesson" or "task", and "de casa" means "from home" or "home". Put together, it refers to the assignments students complete at home.</div><div><strong>e</strong> This word translates to "and" in English. It’s a conjunction used to connect phrases or clauses.</div><div><strong>depois</strong> This is an adverb meaning "afterwards" or "then". It indicates that the action following it happened after the previous one.</div><div><strong>brincaram</strong> This is the third-person plural past tense form of the verb "brincar", which means "to play". It indicates the action of playing that took place after the homework was completed.</div><div><strong>com</strong> This preposition translates to "with" in English. It is used here to introduce the objects of playing.</div><div><strong>seus</strong> This is a possessive adjective that translates to "their". It refers back to the subject of the sentence, "elas", indicating possession of the toys.</div><div><strong>brinquedos</strong> This is the Portuguese word for "toys". It is the plural form, which coincides with the fact that the subject "elas" implies multiple individuals, so it assumes they have multiple toys.</div>','<h2>Eles venderão sua casa em breve.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and refers to a group of people.</div><div><strong>venderão</strong> This is the future tense of the verb "vender" in Portuguese, which means "to sell". It indicates an action that will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "their" in English when agreeing with "eles". It indicates that the house belongs to "them" (the subject).</div><div><strong>casa</strong> This is a noun meaning "house" in Portuguese. It’s the direct object of the verb "vender" and is what will be sold.</div><div><strong>em breve</strong> This is an adverbial phrase in Portuguese meaning "soon". It modifies the verb "venderão", giving a timeframe for when the house will be sold.</div>','<h2>Elas têm que terminar suas lições de casa.</h2><div><strong>Elas</strong> This is the Portuguese third-person plural feminine pronoun, equivalent to "they" in English when referring to a group of females. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>têm</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "ter", which means "to have" in English. In this sentence, it’s part of a phrase "têm que" which translates to "have to", indicating an obligation.</div><div><strong>que</strong> This is a Portuguese conjunction or preposition often used to introduce a subordinate clause. In combination with the verb "ter" (têm), it means "have to" or "must", indicating necessity.</div><div><strong>terminar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the Portuguese verb "terminar", which means "to finish" or "to end" in English. It’s the main action that the subjects need to perform.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, in its plural feminine form, meaning "their" in English. It’s used here to show that the homework belongs to "them" (elas).</div><div><strong>lições de casa</strong> This is a Portuguese noun phrase, where "lições" means "lessons" or "homework", and "de casa" translates to "of home". Together, this phrase means "homework". It’s the object of the verb "terminar", denoting what needs to be finished.</div>','<h2>Eles se lembrarão de suas férias.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>se</strong> This word is a reflexive pronoun in Portuguese. Here, it is used with the verb "lembrar" to mean "to remember" something themselves.</div><div><strong>lembrarão</strong> This is the third-person plural future tense form of the verb "lembrar", which means "to remember". In this sentence, it indicates a future action that will take place.</div><div><strong>de</strong> This Portuguese preposition is equivalent to "of" or "about" in English. It’s used here to indicate the topic of remembrance.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in Portuguese, meaning "their". It is in the plural form to match "férias" (holidays) and to refer back to "eles" (they).</div><div><strong>férias</strong> This is a plural noun in Portuguese, meaning "vacation" or "holidays". It is the object of what "they" will remember.</div>','<h2>As crianças aprendiam a usar sua imaginação.</h2><div><strong>As</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese for feminine plural nouns, meaning "the". It is used here to specify the children being talked about.</div><div><strong>crianças</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "children". It is feminine and plural to match the article "as".</div><div><strong>aprendiam</strong> This is the third-person plural imperfect tense form of the verb "aprender", which means "to learn". It indicates a continuous or repeated action in the past.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the preposition "to" in Portuguese. It is used here to link the verb "aprendiam" with the following infinitive verb "usar", forming the phrase "learn to use".</div><div><strong>usar</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb meaning "to use" in Portuguese. Following the preposition "a", it indicates the action the children were learning to perform.</div><div><strong>sua</strong> This is a possessive adjective meaning "their" in English (although it literally means "his, her, its, your (formal)" reflecting the sex and the number of the owner; here, it’s understood as "their" from the context). It shows ownership or relation to the "children" mentioned.</div><div><strong>imaginação</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "imagination". It is feminine and singular, matching the possessive adjective "sua".</div>','<h2>Eles descerão a colina em suas pranchas de snowboard.</h2><div><strong>Eles</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in Portuguese, equivalent to "they" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>descerão</strong> This is the third-person plural future tense form of the verb "descer", which means "to go down" or "to descend". It indicates a future action.</div><div><strong>a</strong> This is the definite article in Portuguese, equivalent to "the" in English. It is feminine singular to agree with the noun it defines, "colina".</div><div><strong>colina</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "hill". It is the object of the action where the subject will descend.</div><div><strong>em</strong> This is a preposition in Portuguese, representing "in" or "on" in English. It’s used to indicate the method or state.</div><div><strong>suas</strong> This is a possessive adjective in Portuguese, equivalent to "their" in English. It is used to indicate that the snowboards belong to the subject "eles".</div><div><strong>pranchas</strong> This is a Portuguese noun meaning "boards". In this context, it refers specifically to snowboards. It is plural to match with "suas".</div><div><strong>de</strong> This is another preposition in Portuguese, often translated as "of" or "from" in English. Here it’s used as part of the compound noun "pranchas de snowboard".</div><div><strong>snowboard</strong> This is a borrowed term from English, commonly used in Portuguese for the winter sport of snowboarding, here used to refer to the boards used for this sport.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);